<BaseLayout title="New Year's Day — Unmasking the Holidays — Nazaryah" description="New Year's Day honors Janus, the two-faced Roman god of doorways and beginnings. January is named after him. Yahuah's year does not begin in January.">
  <div class="hol-wrap">
    <section class="hol-hero">
      <p class="hol-series">&#8213; Unmasking the Holidays · January &#8213;</p>
      <h1 class="hol-title">New Year's Day</h1>
      <p class="hol-sub">20 Traditions. One Roman god. A year that was never yours to celebrate.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="hol-section">
      <div class="hol-prose">
        <p>New Year's Day (January 1st) honors Janus, the two-faced Roman god of doorways, transitions, and beginnings. January is named after him. The concept of "looking back and looking forward" — which defines the entire cultural mood of New Year's — is Janus's defining characteristic. He was depicted with two faces: one looking into the past, one into the future.</p>
        <p>Yahuah's year does not begin in January. It begins in the month of Aviv, in the spring (Exodus 12:2). The entire Gregorian calendar is a Roman construction that replaced Yahuah's lunar calendar with pagan names and pagan dates. The midnight celebration, the resolutions (vows once made to Babylonian gods), the countdown — all trace to Roman and Babylonian ritual.</p>
        <p>This study examines 20 New Year's traditions — their origins, their meaning, and what Yahuah actually established as the beginning of His year.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
    <section class="hol-coming">
      <div class="hol-coming-inner">
        <div class="hol-coming-icon">&#9685;</div>
        <h2 class="hol-coming-title">Full Study Coming</h2>
        <p>This study is being assembled. Return to the <a href="/holidays" class="hol-link">Holidays hub</a> or explore <a href="/sun-worship/sacred-act" class="hol-link">The Sacred Act</a> while this page is built.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
    <div class="hol-nav">
      <a href="/holidays" class="hol-nav-link">&#8592; All Holidays</a>
      <a href="/holidays/valentines-day" class="hol-nav-link">Valentine's Day &#8594;</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
